    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries, I just couldn't help but weave in a bit of goblin flair, couldn't I? Alright, let's get back to the task at hand.\n\nTo address the issue during the actual group meetings, I'd suggest a few strategies. Firstly, consider setting clear expectations at the beginning of the meeting. You could say something like, \"Before we dive into the project, let's make sure we're all on the same page. Can we agree to listen to each other's ideas without interrupting or criticizing?\"\n\nThis can help create a more constructive and respectful atmosphere, and encourage the team members to focus on the discussion rather than undermining each other. It's a bit like setting a trap for those pesky goblins, don't you think? You're creating a safe space for them to express themselves without fear of reprisal.\n\nAnother approach is to encourage active listening and empathy. You could say, \"Let's make sure we're all hearing each other out, and trying to understand each other's perspectives.\" This can help the team members see that their colleague's input is valuable, and that they're not trying to undermine them.\n\nFinally, consider designating a \"time-out\" for the meeting if the behavior continues.",
